I&rsquo;ll write here about the fundamentals of good zone O. These will, I hope, reveal some underlying principles that any team can apply to its specific strategy/terminology, and to specific situations (e.g., how to deal with a sideline trip). I&rsquo;ll rely on my co-contributors to address those specifics in detail, and read with interest!
So, getting down to basics&hellip;
To figure out how our zone offense should work, we should think about what makes good zone defense successful.

&ldquo;Be careful what you wish for.&rdquo;
— Ken Dobyns over the phone, NYC to Hampton Bays, August 1995.
Calling the D line that season isn&rsquo;t something I necessarily wished for, but blindly accepted the vacancy; possibly a dumb move for a not proved new face on a second year team still fielding much of the leftover NYNY dynasty. We beat Boston four times that season: Regionals, Tune-up, and two small pre- season tourneys.

The best thing I ever heard of for improving your receiving skills is this game called &ldquo;catch&rdquo;&hellip;
There&rsquo;s no replacement for repetition. You just have to do it over and over until you forget what it&rsquo;s like to drop a frisbee.
The next step is simulating game situations. Personally, I feel like the most valuable catch to be 100% on is the in-cut: running full speed toward a disc coming at you.
